Europe's debt write-downs are inevitable
Berkeley —— "That was just the Greek crisis," or "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think, but no longer, because it is clearly now a eurozone crisis.
Dealing with it will be both easier and more difficult than usually imagined.
The economics of this crisis are quite simple.
Greece has fiscal problems.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has issues.
Spain faces problems in all three areas mentioned.
Despite the different details, the conclusion is the same: these countries will all have to go through painful austerity processes.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic spending cuts with currency devaluation.
Devaluation would enhance export competitiveness by substituting foreign demand for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all part of the eurozone and do not have their own independent currencies to devalue, so they must rely on internal devaluation instead.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to increase export competitiveness and thereby boost foreign demand.
In fact, the determination of these crisis countries to tighten their belts is considerable.
But one economic variable has not changed with the adjustments of others – public and private sector debt.
Government books show no change in the face value of accumulated debt, and bank debts – except for some owed to ordinary creditors (junior creditors) – have remained largely unchanged.
This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy in a self-defeating position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes relative to income.
The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be cut and taxes increased to service the government and its defenders (such as banks).
This, in turn, requires further internal devaluation, which raises the debt burden even higher, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into recession.
So, for internal devaluation to work, there must be a way to reduce the face value of the debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt should be converted into equity, and banks that are insolvent should be written off.
Mortgage debt also needs to be reduced.
Policymakers are understandably reluctant to go down this path.
Contracts are sacred.
The government is concerned about losing credibility in financial markets.
If creditors are mainly foreign, especially foreign banks, haircuts would only drag down other countries.
These concerns are not without merit, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two options: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose one or the other.
They all ruled out external devaluation.
But internal devaluation inevitably requires debt restructuring.
To deny this is neither logical nor sensible.
Debt restructuring is straightforward.
The government could issue new bonds at a discount relative to the face value of existing debts.
Bondholders can choose either to exchange their bonds at face value but with later maturities and lower interest rates, or to accept discounted bonds with earlier maturities and higher interest rates.
This is not cutting-edge technology; it has been done before.
But for it to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
First, bondholders must be assured of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone needs to come forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was carried out under the Brady Plan, the US Treasury played the role of the "guarantor big brother."
Today, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, one country's restructuring would raise expectations for others, leading to spillover effects.
Finally, banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring must have their balance sheets strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests, not the perfunctory exercises carried out earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital shortfalls, a comprehensive equity-for-debt swap will be needed for the affected banks.
If that is not enough, government capital infusions will be necessary for the affected banks.
This too requires coordinated action across countries.
Once bank balance sheets have been strengthened, it may be possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private-sector debts without destabilizing the financial system.
Now for the biggest hurdle.
All of this requires firm leadership.
German leaders must acknowledge that German banks face significant exposure to the debt of peripheral eurozone countries, and the situation is urgent.
They must convince both stakeholders and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to take such measures, it should shoulder this responsibility willingly.
In short, European leaders, particularly those in Germany, need to paint a much grimmer picture – or else disaster looms.
Because that is the fact.
